const narrativeIntro = [
  "Rancho Cucamonga is one of the more interesting service markets we cover. On one end of the spectrum you've got the Alta Loma tract homes — solid 1980s and '90s single-family houses where Whirlpool and Maytag are still running well past their expected lifespan. On the other end, you've got the newer estates near Victoria Gardens and Day Creek where Sub-Zero columns, Wolf ranges, and 48-inch built-in refrigerators are standard. Our techs work both worlds in the same day.",
  "The climate here is something no other part of our service area matches. Inland Empire summers hit 105–112°F regularly. That's not the same as Pasadena at 98°F or even the Valley at 102°F. At those sustained temperatures, condenser coils clog faster, compressors run hotter, and appliances that would last 15 years in a coastal climate start showing stress at year 10. We've seen Sub-Zero units in Etiwanda with coil packs that looked like they hadn't been cleaned in a decade — owners had no idea condenser maintenance was even a thing.",
  "There's also the dust factor. Rancho Cucamonga sits at the foot of the San Gabriel Mountains and gets strong Santa Ana winds that push fine particulate through everything. Dryer vent runs in the tract homes here are often 15–20 feet through the garage — longer than the recommended maximum. When you combine that run length with Inland Empire dust, lint accumulates fast. We clear blocked dryer vents on almost every third dryer call in this city.",
];

